# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# zelosMCP Benchmarks — Secrets / Environment Variables
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Copy this file to `.bench.env` and fill in the values.
# The benchmark CLI auto-detects `.bench.env` in the working directory
# or the benchmarks/ directory. Existing env vars take precedence.
#
# This file is committed to the repo as a reference. `.bench.env` is
# gitignored and should NEVER be committed.
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Cursor ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# API key from https://cursor.com/settings (starts with crsr_)
CURSOR_API_KEY=

# ── GitHub Copilot (CLI) ───────────────────────────────────────────
# The Copilot adapter uses the official `copilot` CLI which handles
# auth natively via a one-time device-flow login:
#
#   1. Install:  npm i -g @github/copilot   (or: brew install copilot-cli)
#   2. Login:    copilot /login
#
# For CI / headless environments where interactive login is not
# possible, set GITHUB_TOKEN to a token with Copilot access:
#
#   - Fine-grained PAT with "GitHub Copilot" permission
#   - Classic PAT with `copilot` scope
#   - `gh auth token` output (if gh is logged in with Copilot access)
#
# GITHUB_TOKEN is also used as a fallback when no interactive session
# exists on a developer machine.
GITHUB_TOKEN=

# ── GitHub OAuth (alternative) ─────────────────────────────────────
# If your organisation uses OAuth apps for Copilot access, you can
# provide the OAuth client credentials here. These are used by the
# zelosMCP Python server's OAuth passthrough, not directly by the
# benchmark CLI.
# GITHUB_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=
# GITHUB_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=
